going by dusk or evening

00:33:46.064 --> 00:33:47.480
and they won't be
able to find it.

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:49.200
So it's totally cryptic.

00:33:49.200 --> 00:33:52.100
The rest of the computer
is hidden down here.

00:33:52.100 --> 00:33:54.500
Don't feel bad, because even
these Kenya Wildlife Service

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:56.120
rangers couldn't find it either.

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:59.510
So we demoed this last summer.

00:33:59.510 --> 00:34:02.960
And now, with a new
version is going out there

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:05.750
that we're ready to
go to scale with this.

00:34:05.750 --> 00:34:07.850
The other device that we
have is called AmbushCam.

00:34:07.850 --> 00:34:10.790
So all those rangers, they
told us most of what we do

00:34:10.790 --> 00:34:15.840
is we protect-- we go after
poachers by sending ambushes.

00:34:15.840 --> 00:34:16.920
We get some intelligence.

00:34:16.920 --> 00:34:19.020
We're just not
wandering aimlessly.

00:34:19.020 --> 00:34:22.520
And the idea here is
that being on an ambush

00:34:22.520 --> 00:34:23.505
is really dangerous.

00:34:23.505 --> 00:34:26.130
And also, really boring because
they could be for hours or days

00:34:26.130 --> 00:34:29.889
on end on the trail waiting
for poachers to come down.

00:34:29.889 --> 00:34:33.840
Our new idea of AmbushCam is you
put the eyeballs on the trail.

00:34:33.840 --> 00:34:38.550
So we have the passive
infrared sensor here.

00:34:38.550 --> 00:34:41.940
We have a flare [INAUDIBLE]
camera here that

00:34:41.940 --> 00:34:45.290
streams the video
to rangers who are

00:34:45.290 --> 00:34:48.870
off the trail in their bivouac,
probably not talking loudly,

00:34:48.870 --> 00:34:50.510
but they could be
eating, sleeping.

00:34:50.510 --> 00:34:52.600
One ranger is on duty.

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:54.530
And he's wearing
these goggles that

00:34:54.530 --> 00:34:56.710
have an earpiece in
them that sends a beep

00:34:56.710 --> 00:34:58.830
if the beam is broken.

00:34:58.830 --> 00:35:01.200
And then, streaming video
to see how many poachers

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:02.520
are coming down the trail.

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:05.640
And they can then
set the ambush.

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:07.650
As a spin-off of
that, we've also

00:35:07.650 --> 00:35:09.470
created the world's
cheapest night

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:13.140
vision goggles that we can
make, we think, for about $400.

00:35:13.140 --> 00:35:15.530
Rather than the sort
of $3,000 to $4,000

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:18.570
that military-grade night
vision goggles go for.

00:35:18.570 --> 00:35:20.550
With the idea being
that every ranger that

00:35:20.550 --> 00:35:23.940
is out on night patrols to
protect wildlife in Africa

00:35:23.940 --> 00:35:26.760
should be-- a standard equipment
should have these cheap night

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:27.410
vision goggles.

00:35:27.410 --> 00:35:30.721
So we're taking those over
now to do one more prototype.

00:35:30.721 --> 00:35:32.720
And we hope to go into
production-- [EXPLOSION].

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:37.590
The other idea-- if we want
to go more militaristic--

00:35:37.590 --> 00:35:40.900
is a very heavily-armed
group of poachers come down

00:35:40.900 --> 00:35:44.410
with AK-47's, either you
can just let them go.

00:35:44.410 --> 00:35:47.790
Or the next passive
infrared sensor

00:35:47.790 --> 00:35:50.440
could then remotely trigger
a flashbang stun grenade.

00:35:50.440 --> 00:35:51.690
And then, disarm the poachers.

00:35:51.690 --> 00:35:54.080
Because typically,
the rangers tell us

00:35:54.080 --> 00:35:56.830
you often only catch
one of the poachers

00:35:56.830 --> 00:35:58.410
because the rest run away.

00:35:58.410 --> 00:36:00.520
This way, you'd be able
to-- where you're allowed

00:36:00.520 --> 00:36:02.340
to do this-- immobilize them.

00:36:02.340 --> 00:36:05.540
And then, safely disarm
them and arrest them.

00:36:05.540 --> 00:36:07.660
So what we're trying
to do though--

00:36:07.660 --> 00:36:08.990
and this is a friend of ours.

00:36:08.990 --> 00:36:11.620
One of our donors at the David
Sheldrick Wildlife Trust.

00:36:11.620 --> 00:36:13.370
Those of you who know
of this in Kenya,

00:36:13.370 --> 00:36:16.430
near Nairobi National Park,
they have an elephant orphanage.

00:36:16.430 --> 00:36:18.650
These are all young
elephants whose mothers

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:19.980
have been poached.

00:36:19.980 --> 00:36:22.520
And they take them there,
raise them, resocialize them,

00:36:22.520 --> 00:36:23.747
and reintroduce them.

00:36:23.747 --> 00:36:25.330
We're working with
the Sheldrick Trust

00:36:25.330 --> 00:36:26.530
on their anti-poaching side.

00:36:26.530 --> 00:36:29.070
This is the first place
we're deploying them widely

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:32.040
with the trail guards and ambush
cams and night vision googles,

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:34.760
with the idea of not
making any more orphans.

00:36:34.760 --> 00:36:37.310
So that's really our mission.

00:36:37.310 --> 00:36:40.160
Very quickly, I'm just going
to talk about two more things.

00:36:40.160 --> 00:36:42.160
So one is about--
back to tigers,

00:36:42.160 --> 00:36:45.960
is the fate of tigers is tied
up with humans, of course.

00:36:45.960 --> 00:36:49.930
In India, we have 60% of the
world's tigers living amidst

00:36:49.930 --> 00:36:51.560
a billion people.

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:54.060
And how do we configure
the landscapes

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:56.520
so that we can leave
space for tigers

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:58.240
and leave space
for humans as well?

00:36:58.240 --> 00:37:00.070
So part of our study
that we're doing

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:02.950
that's powered by Google Earth
Engine published in "Science

00:37:02.950 --> 00:37:06.932
Advances" last
April, was a paper

00:37:06.932 --> 00:37:08.765
called "Tracking Changes
and Preventing Loss

00:37:08.765 --> 00:37:10.420
in Critical Tiger Habitat."

00:37:10.420 --> 00:37:13.850
So these are the 76 tiger
conservation landscapes

00:37:13.850 --> 00:37:16.430
scattered across Southeast
Asia and the Russian Far

00:37:16.430 --> 00:37:18.370
East in an inset here.

00:37:18.370 --> 00:37:21.130
And the 76 are scored
either as what we call T

00:37:21.130 --> 00:37:23.970
times 2, TCLs or non-T times 2.

00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:26.171
Meaning the ones in
magenta here are the ones

00:37:26.171 --> 00:37:28.670
that are going to contribute
most to doubling the wild tiger

00:37:28.670 --> 00:37:30.100
population in 12 years.

00:37:30.100 --> 00:37:32.700
They have the healthiest,
largest populations.

00:37:32.700 --> 00:37:35.790
What we can do using Google
Earth Engine and the data

00:37:35.790 --> 00:37:38.380
from Matt [? Hansen ?]
is to track changes

00:37:38.380 --> 00:37:40.040
in the habitat of tigers.

00:37:40.040 --> 00:37:42.890
Because to get to
T times 2, we need

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:44.580
to have a certain
amount of habitat.

00:37:44.580 --> 00:37:48.090
Because tigers are territorial,
different size territories.

00:37:48.090 --> 00:37:50.470
How much area do we
need to set aside

00:37:50.470 --> 00:37:52.750
to be able to protect them?

00:37:52.750 --> 00:37:55.140
And what we found, the
results were remarkable.

00:37:55.140 --> 00:37:59.250
Over the 14 year period, we
expected a tremendous amount

00:37:59.250 --> 00:38:00.642
of loss of habitat.

00:38:00.642 --> 00:38:02.600
Because these are the
fastest-growing economies

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:04.870
in the world, high
rural population

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:07.880
densities in India, Nepal,
Bangladesh, and a few others.

00:38:07.880 --> 00:38:13.940
We've only lost about
7% of the tiger habitat

00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:15.020
over this 14-year period.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:17.460
We thought it would
be more like 21%.

00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:19.770
So that's a really
great finding.

00:38:19.770 --> 00:38:22.920
Equally important is there
is still enough habitat

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:26.010
left in the tiger range
to allow for not only

00:38:26.010 --> 00:38:29.030
a doubling of wild tigers,
but almost even a tripling.

00:38:29.030 --> 00:38:32.880
Which we only found out because
of the value of Google Earth

00:38:32.880 --> 00:38:36.390
Engine and Global Forest Watch
to be able to compute this,

00:38:36.390 --> 00:38:38.440
which we couldn't
do two years ago.

00:38:38.440 --> 00:38:41.490
So we're now doing-- to show
this can work at the Terai Arc

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:46.101
landscape where-- my book
takes place right here.

00:38:46.101 --> 00:38:48.350
We're going to zoom in on a
couple of these corridors.

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:51.510
So another critical important
piece of tiger biology,

00:38:51.510 --> 00:38:54.650
tigers have to-- male
tigers have to disperse.

00:38:54.650 --> 00:38:56.730
They can't stay in
their natal home range

00:38:56.730 --> 00:38:58.690
or the adult male
will kill them.

00:38:58.690 --> 00:39:00.840
And tigers are relatively
poor dispersers,

00:39:00.840 --> 00:39:02.340
unlike, say, wolves.

00:39:02.340 --> 00:39:05.140
So you have to have relatively
interconnected forest

00:39:05.140 --> 00:39:08.490
corridors for tigers to
go from A to B to C to D.

00:39:08.490 --> 00:39:13.424
So we can use the new
approach we have to zoom in.

00:39:13.424 --> 00:39:14.840
This is really the
most-- not only

00:39:14.840 --> 00:39:17.390
look at the whole scale
of the tiger habitat

00:39:17.390 --> 00:39:20.080
and look at changes
annually, but move in

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:23.270
and look at changes in
these critical corridors.

00:39:23.270 --> 00:39:26.140
And to show that
here in this one,

00:39:26.140 --> 00:39:28.800
in the [? Basanta ?]
Corridor, we've actually lost

00:39:28.800 --> 00:39:33.400
habitat here in this critical
connector piece right here.

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:35.030
And here in the
[? Kata ?] Corridor,

00:39:35.030 --> 00:39:37.530
we've actually
gained habitat, which

00:39:37.530 --> 00:39:40.710
you can see not so well here.

00:39:40.710 --> 00:39:42.225
But there's a
number-- right here.

00:39:42.225 --> 00:39:45.550
Yeah, these blue polygons here
are where community forestry

00:39:45.550 --> 00:39:48.930
programs have helped reestablish
connectivity with India.

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:52.580
The tigers in this park
have gone from 18 to 50

00:39:52.580 --> 00:39:53.900
in the last five years.

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:55.470
In part because of
better protection,

00:39:55.470 --> 00:39:58.390
but also because of movement
back and forth from India.

00:39:58.390 --> 00:40:00.600
So we have a whole new
tool at our disposal

00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:02.100
now to better manage tigers.

00:40:02.100 --> 00:40:04.830
And look across which
of the 76 landscapes

00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:06.400
are the ones that
have lost the most

00:40:06.400 --> 00:40:08.510
amount of absolute habitat.

00:40:08.510 --> 00:40:10.260
And what percent of it?

00:40:10.260 --> 00:40:12.519
And now, the tiger range
states-- most important--

00:40:12.519 --> 00:40:14.310
they're using this as
their monitoring tool

00:40:14.310 --> 00:40:16.570
to measure progress
towards conserving that.

00:40:16.570 --> 00:40:19.220
We're just about to receive a
grant this week from the Arcus

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:21.570
Foundation in working with
the Jane Goodall Institute

00:40:21.570 --> 00:40:25.670
to do the same analysis
for African and Asian apes

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:26.540
in the next year.

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:29.140
So very useful way
of looking at that.

00:40:29.140 --> 00:40:31.570
And now, I'm going to
end with just saving you

00:40:31.570 --> 00:40:34.360
the heartache of going and
doing a PhD in conservation

00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:36.540
biology at Stanford, say.

00:40:36.540 --> 00:40:40.030
I'm going to reduce conservation
biology into one sentence.

00:40:40.030 --> 00:40:41.970
One phrase, even.

00:40:41.970 --> 00:40:44.440
Pay attention to the
landscapes and beta-diversity.

00:40:44.440 --> 00:40:47.370
So the first part was--
I showed you on tigers

00:40:47.370 --> 00:40:49.950
and the apes is-- some
of the critical species

00:40:49.950 --> 00:40:52.390
we have to save, you
need to take a landscape

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:53.850
approach to conservation.

00:40:53.850 --> 00:40:56.610
That protected areas by
themselves are too small.

00:40:56.610 --> 00:40:58.370
There's not a single
protected area

00:40:58.370 --> 00:41:01.350
in the entire tiger
range large enough

00:41:01.350 --> 00:41:03.630
to maintain a viable population.

00:41:03.630 --> 00:41:06.620
So what you need to do is
to have linked reserves

00:41:06.620 --> 00:41:09.840
where tigers are managed as a
meta-population, a population

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:11.510
linked by dispersal.

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:14.590
That's what we have to do at
one extreme for what we call

00:41:14.590 --> 00:41:16.050
"area-sensitive species."

00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:19.860
Tigers, elephants,
jaguars, et cetera.

00:41:19.860 --> 00:41:21.500
Harpy eagles.

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:24.090
At the other extreme
is beta-diversity.

00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:25.820
Of species that
are highly endemic,

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:28.810
what beta-diversity is-- it's
just a piece of eco jargon

00:41:28.810 --> 00:41:32.090
that means the turnover
of species along gradients

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:33.480
or with distance.

00:41:33.480 --> 00:41:35.630
And what you have
to do then is if you

00:41:35.630 --> 00:41:39.070
have a high turnover of
species is to put reserves

00:41:39.070 --> 00:41:42.440
in enough places where
they're distinct to protect

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:43.380
those populations.

00:41:43.380 --> 00:41:45.630
So whether they're
chameleons in Madagascar

00:41:45.630 --> 00:41:49.450
or highly-endangered parrots
in Colombia, bird wing

00:41:49.450 --> 00:41:53.540
butterflies, or rare
plants, spacing the reserves

00:41:53.540 --> 00:41:55.380
in the right places is critical.

00:41:55.380 --> 00:41:59.070
That if we can capture this
pattern of turnover species

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:03.240
with distance and these vast
areas we need for conservation,

00:42:03.240 --> 00:42:05.070
then we've pretty
much conserved 90%

00:42:05.070 --> 00:42:06.950
of all species and processes.

00:42:06.950 --> 00:42:09.830
And that's the crux of
conservation biology.

00:42:09.830 --> 00:42:12.170
How that's playing
out is a new project

00:42:12.170 --> 00:42:15.260
that we hope to involve
our colleagues at Google

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:17.150
with that's called
Nature Needs Half.

00:42:17.150 --> 00:42:21.310
And Tanya said at the
end of my introduction

00:42:21.310 --> 00:42:22.850
the Pope of
Conservation Biology,

00:42:22.850 --> 00:42:24.850
E.O. Wilson, has come out
with a new book called

00:42:24.850 --> 00:42:27.410
"Half Earth," which
calls for putting half

00:42:27.410 --> 00:42:30.010
of the terrestrial realm
and half of the marine

00:42:30.010 --> 00:42:32.510
under some form of
conservation management

00:42:32.510 --> 00:42:35.250
if our species is
to survive and if we

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:37.520
are to save all the
other species on Earth.

00:42:37.520 --> 00:42:41.200
So our approach of doing that
is to revisit a map that we

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:43.950
published in 2001 in the
"Journal of Bioscience"

00:42:43.950 --> 00:42:46.160
called "Terrestrial Eco
Regions of the World,"

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:49.100
where we divide eco
regions not by countries--

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:52.280
not look at it by country,
but by eco regions.

00:42:52.280 --> 00:42:54.970
And you can see how,
like here is Brazil.

00:42:54.970 --> 00:42:55.720
The boundary here.

00:42:55.720 --> 00:42:58.610
How eco region boundaries
or natures boundaries don't

00:42:58.610 --> 00:43:00.800
follow political boundaries.

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:03.830
What we've done is to
apply this idea of nature

00:43:03.830 --> 00:43:07.050
needs half to the
846 eco regions

00:43:07.050 --> 00:43:10.740
that will be in this new
map called Eco Regions 2.0.

00:43:10.740 --> 00:43:13.590
And to see how far we
are on our progress

00:43:13.590 --> 00:43:15.970
of saving half of wild nature.

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:18.280
So we divide them
into four categories

00:43:18.280 --> 00:43:22.340
of places that have already
exceeded 50% protection, places

00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:25.730
that could do that, places
that with a lot of restoration

00:43:25.730 --> 00:43:27.970
could do that, and
places that-- good luck,

00:43:27.970 --> 00:43:29.710
its nature is really imperiled.

00:43:29.710 --> 00:43:33.630
You know, the idea of taking the
Tallgrass Prairie of Illinois,

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:37.980
which is 99% soybeans
and corn would probably

00:43:37.980 --> 00:43:40.110
require the end of
the civilized world

00:43:40.110 --> 00:43:42.680
to ever get back
to nature in this.

00:43:42.680 --> 00:43:44.720
So we're not being naive.

00:43:44.720 --> 00:43:47.190
There are a lot of places--
not a lot of places

00:43:47.190 --> 00:43:48.340
that can't do that.

00:43:48.340 --> 00:43:50.840
But the surprising
and positive finding

00:43:50.840 --> 00:43:53.400
is there are many eco
regions, perhaps a third

00:43:53.400 --> 00:43:56.230
already, that either
have the ability

00:43:56.230 --> 00:43:59.160
to protect-- that have already
protected half or close to it,

00:43:59.160 --> 00:44:01.430
40%, or could do so.

00:44:01.430 --> 00:44:03.840
So that it's not as
far-fetched as we think.

00:44:03.840 --> 00:44:06.810
And so we're hoping
that this becomes,

00:44:06.810 --> 00:44:10.190
really, the new conservation
paradigm of the next century.

00:44:10.190 --> 00:44:13.280
That if we are to leave
behind a living planet,

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:15.770
we have to undertake
the exercises to plan--

00:44:15.770 --> 00:44:17.940
to zone for
conservation and zone

00:44:17.940 --> 00:44:21.050
for intensive human development
in the right places.

00:44:21.050 --> 00:44:24.640
So that we leave space for the
tigers and rhinos and elephants

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:28.760
of Bardiya that I had the great
chance to study when I was 21.

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:31.800
And leave things for
future generations as well.

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:33.218
So thank you very much.

00:44:33.218 --> 00:44:37.870
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:37.870 --> 00:44:41.410
AUDIENCE: So for the
Nature Needs Half,

00:44:41.410 --> 00:44:47.540
how much of the success there
is dependent on governments

00:44:47.540 --> 00:44:49.495
buying into it?

00:44:49.495 --> 00:44:50.870
ERIC DINERSTEIN:
So the question,

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:53.225
how much of Nature Needs
Half is getting governments

00:44:53.225 --> 00:44:53.850
to buy into it?

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:55.160
Absolutely.

00:44:55.160 --> 00:44:57.910
So one of the things we
talk about in the paper

00:44:57.910 --> 00:45:02.210
is that almost every government,
except the United States

00:45:02.210 --> 00:45:05.470
and Bhutan has signed on to
the Convention of Biodiversity.

00:45:05.470 --> 00:45:08.930
And in that are a set of
targets that they're supposed

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:10.760
to reach by a certain date.

00:45:10.760 --> 00:45:13.040
And so in this case,
they're codified

00:45:13.040 --> 00:45:14.920
as the [? Ichee ?] targets.

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:17.820
And [? Ichee ?]
target 11 is aiming

00:45:17.820 --> 00:45:22.580
for 17% of the terrestrial
realm conserved by 2020.

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:27.820
Right now, the global
amount is 15.4%.

00:45:27.820 --> 00:45:31.770
We're trying to suggest that is
a really important and useful

00:45:31.770 --> 00:45:35.070
milestone, but not
the end target.

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:38.300
Just because it's
nowhere near enough.

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:40.180
But governments have
bought into that.

00:45:40.180 --> 00:45:42.940
So we're trying to
say, great milestone.

00:45:42.940 --> 00:45:47.130
But over the next 10, 20, 30,
50 years, let's get to 50%.

00:45:47.130 --> 00:45:48.820
But without the help
of the governments,

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:50.860
it won't be possible.

00:45:50.860 --> 00:45:53.810
And however, the 50%
can also incorporate--

00:45:53.810 --> 00:45:55.550
and will incorporate
indigenous reserves,

00:45:55.550 --> 00:45:58.760
which are vast expanses of
some parts of the world.

00:45:58.760 --> 00:45:59.822
Private reserves.

00:45:59.822 --> 00:46:01.280
So there are other
ways that we can

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:05.180
get to 50% besides
just protected areas.

00:46:05.180 --> 00:46:07.700
But that will be
certainly the cornerstone.

00:46:07.700 --> 00:46:11.830
AUDIENCE: Let's say you take
an area and divide it in half.

00:46:11.830 --> 00:46:15.230
And you have 50%
preserved, or conserved,

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:17.580
or managed in some way.

00:46:17.580 --> 00:46:19.830
Now, let's say that you
take each of those halves

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:22.550
and divide it in half like
a checkerboard pattern.

00:46:22.550 --> 00:46:24.210
And you keep doing that.

00:46:24.210 --> 00:46:28.290
And eventually, you get a very
dispersed pattern that still

00:46:28.290 --> 00:46:31.840
represents 50% of the area.

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:33.447
Which of those is better?

00:46:33.447 --> 00:46:34.780
ERIC DINERSTEIN: Great question.

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:37.380
So what you've just
described is really

00:46:37.380 --> 00:46:39.460
fragmentation of habitat.

00:46:39.460 --> 00:46:43.344
And depending on where
you are-- so the answer,

00:46:43.344 --> 00:46:45.093
like everything in
science, is it depends.

00:46:48.370 --> 00:46:53.470
But in most cases, the more
connected, the more there

00:46:53.470 --> 00:46:56.110
is habitat integrity,
the better the chances

00:46:56.110 --> 00:46:59.360
are of conserving not
just the species there

00:46:59.360 --> 00:47:02.720
that need big areas, but the
phenomenon that occur there

00:47:02.720 --> 00:47:04.040
that drive the whole ecology.

00:47:04.040 --> 00:47:07.670
So for example, if we were in
the Boreal Forest in Canada

00:47:07.670 --> 00:47:10.160
right now, it's
these-- well, somebody

00:47:10.160 --> 00:47:12.160
would call it cataclysmic,
but others would just

00:47:12.160 --> 00:47:15.680
say extensive forest fires that
really drive those systems.

00:47:15.680 --> 00:47:17.770
So your protected area
should be large enough

00:47:17.770 --> 00:47:22.030
to contain either giant
insect outbreaks that

00:47:22.030 --> 00:47:26.090
lead to a loss of trees or
these giant forest fires.

00:47:26.090 --> 00:47:29.400
To be big enough to contain
those ecological events

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:30.850
and still persist.

00:47:30.850 --> 00:47:31.600
And still recover.

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:35.940
For rain forest
versus grasslands,

00:47:35.940 --> 00:47:38.900
like-- one of the things
we say in our paper

00:47:38.900 --> 00:47:42.770
is that 50% is a
guideline, an aspirational.

00:47:42.770 --> 00:47:45.270
But it's also not prescriptive.

00:47:45.270 --> 00:47:48.270
It's an empirically-derived
estimate

00:47:48.270 --> 00:47:51.199
that should come from studying
the biology of the species

00:47:51.199 --> 00:47:51.990
in that eco region.

00:47:51.990 --> 00:47:55.480
So to give you an example,
in a lot of rain forests

00:47:55.480 --> 00:47:58.580
where you have very
high beta-diversity,

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:01.350
you want lots of
reserves spaced depending

00:48:01.350 --> 00:48:04.000
on where the distributions
of those species are.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.980
But in the Amazon
basin, there's estimates

00:48:06.980 --> 00:48:09.830
that if we don't maintain
80% forest cover in those eco

00:48:09.830 --> 00:48:14.840
regions, we lose the biophysical
function of the Amazon

00:48:14.840 --> 00:48:16.880
as a weather machine
that makes its own rain.

00:48:16.880 --> 00:48:20.130
Of how the rainfall that
comes off of the trade winds

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:23.230
gets recycled 10 times
before it hits the Andes,

00:48:23.230 --> 00:48:27.350
and then moves back to provide
the precipitation for the corn

00:48:27.350 --> 00:48:31.080
crop in South Africa or
the wheat crop in Canada.

00:48:31.080 --> 00:48:32.740
A small part of it
makes its way back.

00:48:32.740 --> 00:48:36.990
So there are some eco regions
that need a lot more area.

00:48:36.990 --> 00:48:40.830
For some grasslands, because in
grasslands most of the species

00:48:40.830 --> 00:48:42.380
there tend to be
pretty widespread,

00:48:42.380 --> 00:48:45.680
it could be that a few whopping
big reserves would do better

00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:47.220
than lots of small ones.

00:48:47.220 --> 00:48:49.630
But in general, big
and well-connected

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:52.600
is better than small
and fragmented.

00:48:52.600 --> 00:48:55.521
AUDIENCE: I was just curious on
the tigers and other predators.

00:48:55.521 --> 00:48:57.270
Just curious on the
detail of, how do they

00:48:57.270 --> 00:48:58.430
interact with other predators?

00:48:58.430 --> 00:49:00.471
Do they need range separate
from other predators,

00:49:00.471 --> 00:49:03.170
or do they kind of
not interact at all?

00:49:03.170 --> 00:49:05.500
You know, wild dogs, and
leopards, and all that.

00:49:05.500 --> 00:49:07.230
ERIC DINERSTEIN: So
they do interact.

00:49:07.230 --> 00:49:10.030
And mostly, when you have a
top predator like a tiger,

00:49:10.030 --> 00:49:13.620
the wild dogs and the leopards
try to stay away from them.

00:49:13.620 --> 00:49:16.640
But leopards being much
smaller in body size,

00:49:16.640 --> 00:49:19.450
they have much
smaller home ranges.

00:49:19.450 --> 00:49:23.050
And wild dogs on the opposite
have enormous ranges.

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:25.360
Whether they're Asian
wild dogs, or they're

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:27.200
African painted
dogs or wild dogs,

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:28.440
they have gigantic ranges.

00:49:28.440 --> 00:49:30.700
Because they're often
on the move and they're

00:49:30.700 --> 00:49:32.129
hunting over big areas.

00:49:32.129 --> 00:49:34.170
And probably, in part
they're trying to stay away

00:49:34.170 --> 00:49:36.980
from the top predators.

00:49:36.980 --> 00:49:38.907
So you see that phenomenon.

00:49:38.907 --> 00:49:41.240
I mean, the wild dogs are
also different because they're

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:42.570
social hunters.

00:49:42.570 --> 00:49:45.690
And they can take down, like the
sambar deer, when all of them

00:49:45.690 --> 00:49:47.540
converge on a prey item.

00:49:47.540 --> 00:49:49.870
So they can take things
much bigger than them.

00:49:49.870 --> 00:49:53.630
Leopards, typically, don't
take prey bigger than

00:49:53.630 --> 00:49:57.250
like, say, a sambar deer.

00:49:57.250 --> 00:49:59.480
Some tigers are specialists
on killing things

00:49:59.480 --> 00:50:03.410
like the Indian bison,
which is over 2,000 pounds.

00:50:03.410 --> 00:50:05.590
So even though the
tigers are smaller,

00:50:05.590 --> 00:50:07.870
they're very effective hunters.

00:50:07.870 --> 00:50:11.746
TANYA: I find it very inspiring
and an incredible bright spot

00:50:11.746 --> 00:50:15.270
that Nepal has not seen
an incident of poaching.

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:18.210
Is that something that
you think could be

00:50:18.210 --> 00:50:20.415
replicated in other countries?

00:50:20.415 --> 00:50:21.290
ERIC DINERSTEIN: Yes.

00:50:21.290 --> 00:50:22.640
And it should be.

00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:26.440
So in Nepal-- I've been
working there since 1975.

00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:32.160
But it's taken years to
introduce new policies

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:35.650
and programs that the Nepalese
government, which really

00:50:35.650 --> 00:50:37.600
is incredibly innovative
in a lot of ways,

00:50:37.600 --> 00:50:39.070
has taken and run with.

00:50:39.070 --> 00:50:43.030
One, for example, is we know
that we need to do conservation

00:50:43.030 --> 00:50:44.210
outside the parks.

00:50:44.210 --> 00:50:47.470
And we need to get local people
on our side for conservation

00:50:47.470 --> 00:50:50.120
if it's to have
any lasting value.

00:50:50.120 --> 00:50:53.290
They passed legislation
in the mid-90s to not only

00:50:53.290 --> 00:50:56.020
hand over the forests
outside protected areas

00:50:56.020 --> 00:50:57.770
to local communities
if they could come up

00:50:57.770 --> 00:51:00.240
with good management
plans, but then

00:51:00.240 --> 00:51:03.110
to recycle the revenue--
half the revenues generated

00:51:03.110 --> 00:51:06.820
by the national parks
back to local communities

00:51:06.820 --> 00:51:09.820
for development
for their own use,

00:51:09.820 --> 00:51:12.450
if they come up
with good proposals.

00:51:12.450 --> 00:51:14.230
And that's turned
people around the parks

00:51:14.230 --> 00:51:18.270
who were anti-park before to
conservationists overnight.

00:51:18.270 --> 00:51:21.120
And so in fact, why we
had the recovery of some

00:51:21.120 --> 00:51:23.620
of those wildlife corridors
I showed between the parks

00:51:23.620 --> 00:51:26.710
is because community forestry
programs are actively

00:51:26.710 --> 00:51:29.820
protecting and monitoring
their own community forests.

00:51:29.820 --> 00:51:32.360
And the wildlife is
coming back in them.

00:51:32.360 --> 00:51:33.590
So that's been amazing.

00:51:33.590 --> 00:51:35.090
The other thing
they do is they have

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:36.670
the army in the national parks.

00:51:36.670 --> 00:51:40.090
And that acts as
a major deterrent.

00:51:40.090 --> 00:51:41.847
That's problematic
in some countries.

00:51:41.847 --> 00:51:43.680
But I think the biggest
difference is really

00:51:43.680 --> 00:51:47.820
our successful anti-poaching
information network.

00:51:47.820 --> 00:51:50.550
So intelligence is critical.

00:51:50.550 --> 00:51:53.490
Back in the old days,
we would pay informants

00:51:53.490 --> 00:51:55.290
more than the
poachers would get.

00:51:55.290 --> 00:51:58.410
That's now leveled off a bit
with the value of rhino horn.

00:51:58.410 --> 00:52:02.210
But still, the
transfer of revenues

00:52:02.210 --> 00:52:05.050
from the parks themselves
back to communities

00:52:05.050 --> 00:52:07.340
has given people an
investment in conserving

00:52:07.340 --> 00:52:08.720
rhinos and tigers.

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:10.276
Such that, as I
say, there has not

00:52:10.276 --> 00:52:11.900
been a single rhino,
tiger, or elephant

00:52:11.900 --> 00:52:12.930
poached in three years.

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:14.971
And there's no other
country that can match that.

00:52:14.971 --> 00:52:17.110
So clearly, Nepal is
doing something right.

00:52:17.110 --> 00:52:19.530
Well, thank you very
much for your attention.

00:52:19.530 --> 00:52:20.407
And--

00:52:20.407 --> 00:52:21.990
TANYA: Thank you for
coming to Google.

00:52:21.990 --> 00:52:25.315
[APPLAUSE]

